BM FileNet P8 – CPE JVM & JDBC Tuning Guide
(Linux)
This document provides recommended JVM and JDBC configuration steps to address slow search
performance observed via ACCE / CPE on Linux systems, especially after migration from AIX.
These steps assume DB and LDAP performance have already been validated as healthy.
1. JDBC Statement Cache Configuration
Enable and size the JDBC statement cache to allow reuse of prepared SQL statements used by
FileNet search operations.
1 WebSphere Admin Console → Resources → JDBC → Data sources →
2 Set Statement cache size to 50–100
3 Apply changes and restart the CPE JVM
2. Auto-Commit Verification
Ensure JDBC auto-commit is disabled. Auto-commit ON causes unnecessary transaction overhead
during result fetching.
1 DataSource → Custom properties
2 Verify property autocommit=false (default if not present)
3. JDBC Fetch Size (Critical for Search Performance)
Increase JDBC fetch size to reduce round trips between CPE and DB2 during search result
retrieval.
1 Servers → WebSphere application servers → CPE → Java Virtual Machine
2 Add JVM argument: -Dcom.ibm.db2.jcc.am.fetchSize=1000
3 Restart CPE JVM
4. Recommended JVM Heap & GC Settings (Linux)
Linux JVM defaults are conservative. FileNet CPE requires explicit heap sizing and garbage
collection tuning to efficiently hydrate search results.
1-Xms8g
2-Xmx8g
3-XX:+UseG1GC
4-XX:MaxGCPauseMillis=200
5. DNS / Hostname Resolution Validation
Ensure fast forward and reverse DNS resolution for the CPE host to avoid hidden latency during
JDBC and internal JVM operations.
1 Validate hostname resolution using: hostname -f, getent hosts
2 Ensure proper /etc/hosts entries exist
6. Post-Change Validation
After applying the above settings and restarting CPE, validate improvements by comparing ACCE
search response time and time-to-first-result
